fields.name: Bill Yellowtail
fields.historical_note:
William P. Yellowtail, known as Bill, was born in 1948 on the Crow reservation in Montana.  Bill is the eldest of four children of William Yellowtail and Jane Powers who operated a cattle ranch in the Big Horn Mountains. Bill attended Wyola Elementary School and graduated from Lodge Grass High School in 1963. Holding a degree in geography from Dartmouth College, Bill has been a rancher, educator, fishing guide, Montana State Senator and congressional candidate. An expert canoeist and fly fisherman, he was named Angler of the Year for 1991 by Fly Rod and Reel magazine.

He served as Regional Administrator for the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency during the Clinton administration, with responsibility for six western states and 27 Indian Tribes. Bill received the Dartmouth Environmental Network's 1994 annual award in recognition of his outstanding contributions to protection of the environment, and he received the Mary G. Ross Award for exemplary service from the Council of Energy Resource Tribes in 1999.  He serves on the Boards of Directors of Humanities Montana, the Burton K. Wheeler Center, and the National Audubon Society.
fields.private_notes: Yellowtail can be reached at byellowtail@hotmail.com.

fields.name: Peggy White Wellknown Buffalo
fields.historical_note: "Ba La Se She Lesh " (She Who Wears the Money) grew up traditional Crow. Sent away to Indian boarding schools at a young age, she has nurtured more than 200 children in her home as an adult. She practices the Crow sweat lodge and has sponsored numerous Native American Church prayer meetings. With Susie Kelly, she runs The Center Pole, a Native non-profit organization founded in 1999 on the Crow Indian Reservation in Montana and spearheads many community development projects, including the CIVAM.
fields.address: The Center Pole, PO Box 71, Garryowen, MT, 59031

fields.name: National Museum of American Indian
fields.description: To search the NMAI collections, and the Smithsonian Institution collections in general, go to: https://collections.si.edu/search/
fields.historical_note:
About the Museum

A diverse and multifaceted cultural and educational enterprise, the National Museum of the American Indian (NMAI) is an active and visible component of the Smithsonian Institution, the world's largest museum complex. The NMAI cares for one of the world's most expansive collections of Native artifacts, including objects, photographs, archives, and media covering the entire Western Hemisphere, from the Arctic Circle to Tierra del Fuego.

 The National Museum of the American Indian operates three facilities. The museum on the National Mall in Washington, D.C., offers exhibition galleries and spaces for performances, lectures and symposia, research, and education. The George Gustav Heye Center (GGHC) in New York City houses exhibitions, research, educational activities, and performing arts programs. The Cultural Resources Center (CRC) in Suitland, Maryland, houses the museum's collections as well as the conservation, repatriation, and digital imaging programs, and research facilities. The NMAI's off-site outreach efforts, often referred to as the "fourth museum," include websites, traveling exhibitions, and community programs.

Since the passage of its enabling legislation in 1989 (amended in 1996), the NMAI has been steadfastly committed to bringing Native voices to what the museum writes and presents, whether on-site at one of the three NMAI venues, through the museum's publications, or via the Internet. The NMAI is also dedicated to acting as a resource for the hemisphere's Native communities and to serving the greater public as an honest and thoughtful conduit to Native cultures—present and past—in all their richness, depth, and diversity.
fields.address: Fourth Street & Independence Ave., S.W. Washington, DC 20560

fields.name: Susie Kelly
fields.historical_note: "Dek Gash Bish" (Woman Eagle) helped Peggy create the Center Pole in 1999, bringing practical skills to blend with traditional ways. Originally a photo editor, researcher, writer and project manager in the publishing industry, she brought up multicultural children and worked providing promising youth with opportunities for many years. Her motto: Start where you are...Use what you have...Do what you can--Arthur Ashe.

fields.name: U.S. Department of Interior, Bureau of Indian Affairs, Division of Extension and Industry
Charles S. Runyan
fields.historical_note: Charles S. Runyan was the extension agent for the Bureau of Indian Affairs' Division of Extension and Agency at the Crow reservation, Montana, in the 1930s.  He worked under the supervision of the Crow reservation superintendent Robert Yellowtail.  Runyan wrote a master of science thesis in the department of Agricultural Economics at Montana State College (now Montana State University) in 1939.

From "Crow Tribe May Be Struggling," Billings Gazette (March 26, 2001): "Tilton Old Bull, Sr. Old Bull has been critical of the new administration and his lawyer has filed a class action lawsuit against tribal officials, the Bureau of Indian Affairs, and a local bank, saying the tribe has mismanaged its finances."

fields.name: Kimberly Yellowtail
fields.historical_note: Kimberly Dawn Yellowtail, daughter of Jeanne Eder and William Yellowtail, was born in Hanover, New Hampshire on May 9, 1970. Kim grew up on the Yellowtail family ranch. Even before her teenage years, she became an accomplished cowhand and horsewoman, making her an indispensable part of the ranch's operation. (Information from her father Bill Yellowtail, Jr., May, 2021)

fields.title: Bill Yellowtail photographs, 1960s-2000
fields.description: This collection consists of over 100 photographs taken by William Petzoldt, Jr.( Bill) Yellowtail of ranch life on the Crow Indian reservation, Montana in the mid to late twentieth century. Yellowtail lived around the West and held powerful positions in government, yet ranch life on the reservation has always been home to him. Yellowtail took the photographs with a variety of cameras, using mostly slide color film.  Subjects include ranch activities, such as cattle drives, cow camps, and round-ups. His photographs also depict his family members and their Indian and non-Indian neighbors at work and at play.
fields.provenance: All original slides are in the private collection of Bill Yellowtail
fields.citation: Bill Yellowtail photographs, 1960s-2000
fields.access_notes_or_rights_and_reproduction: Bill Yellowtail has allowed all of his photographs to have unrestricted access and use. fields.title: Peggy White Wellknown Buffalo & Susie Kelly NMAI Crow Heritage Collection
fields.description: Between 2001 and 2008, Peggy Wellknown Buffalo of the Crow Tribe, and Susan Kelly led seven trips with elders from the Crow reservation in Montana to the National Museum of American Indian, Smithsonian Institution in Washington, DC to videotape the Crow elders as they examined and described the history and stories about sacred and non-sacred items in the museum.  This digital collection includes over 2,000 short, individual tapes of Crow items.  Items include headdresses, shields, shirts, rattles, and medicine bundles, among many others.
fields.provenance: Peggy White Wellknown Buffalo and Susie Kelly filmed the items at the National Museum of American Indian between 2001 and 2008 . In 2019, the films were digitized at the University of Delaware history department and the films divided up into individual short film clips for each item in the collection.

fields.title: Crow Indian Gardeners & Farmers, 1930s
fields.description: The collection includes photographs of Crow Indians, with captions, that accompanied annual reports of the U.S. Department of Interior, Bureau of Indian Affairs' Division of Extension and Industry. The Crow reservation extension agent compiled the report and sent it to the Commissioner of Indian Affairs in Washington, D.C. The photographs date from the 1930s and depict Crow Indian adults and youth in agricultural pursuits, 4-H programs, gardening, home economic activities, and in social gatherings. They are seen at feeds (feasts), working in their gardens, harvesting their farm fields, and managing livestock, among other activities. Many of the captions include the names of the individuals and the places depicted in them.
fields.provenance: The photographs in this collection were published in the annual reports of the extension agent for the U.S. Department of Interior, Bureau of Indian Affairs, Division of Extension and Industry at the Crow Reservation. (The text of the reports has not yet been added to the CIVAM collection.) The report photographs were copied by Cindy Ott at the National Archives and Records Administration in Washington, D.C. in March 2015. Cindy Ott organized three exhibitions of a dozen of the photographs at senior centers in the towns of Crow Agency, Lodge Grass, and Pryor on the Crow reservation in summer 2017. (Catalog records of individual photograph document which ones were exhibited.)
fields.citation: See individual photographs for specific citations.
fields.historical_note:
In the early years of the United States, Indian affairs were governed by the Continental Congress, which in 1775 created a Committee on Indian Affairs headed by Benjamin Franklin. Article I, Section 8, of the U.S. Constitution describes Congress's powers over Indian affairs: "To regulate commerce with foreign nations, and among the several States, and with the Indian tribes." The BIA, one of the oldest bureaus in the Federal government, was administratively established by Secretary of War John C. Calhoun on March 11, 1824, to oversee and carry out the Federal government's trade and treaty relations with the tribes. Congress gave the BIA statutory authority by the act of July 9, 1832 (4 Stat. 564, chap. 174). In 1849, the BIA was transferred to the newly created U.S. Department of the Interior. For years thereafter, the Bureau was known variously as the Indian office, the Indian bureau, the Indian department, and the Indian Service. The Interior Department formally adopted the name “Bureau of Indian Affairs” for the agency on September 17, 1947.

The Bureau of Indian Affairs, Division of Extension and Industry was created to document Indian economic activities and ways of life, and the work of the extension agents. Charles S. Runyan was the extension agent who produced the reports under the the supervision of Crow Superintendent Robert Yellowtail in the 1930s.
fields.access_notes_or_rights_and_reproduction: All of these photographs are in the public domain and are, therefore, unrestricted in terms of access, use, and reproduction.  However, we kindly ask those interested in using any image to contact relatives of the individuals depicted in the images for permission to use the images in any way.  Please contact CIVAM at civam.mt@gmail for assistance.
fields.private_notes: There are more BIA Division of Extension and Industry photographs to add to this collection. The Montana Extension Service photographs will also be added to the collection. Copies of all of the reports are in Cindy Ott's private collection.

fields.title: Crow Hymns, 1900-2018
fields.description: Recordings of Crow hymns made in private settings and public gatherings on the Crow Reservation from 1900 to 2018. The oldest recording was made by anthropologist Robert Lowie with Crow people on wax cylinders around 1900. David Graber recorded songs at the Lodge Grass Catholic Church in Lodge Grass and at the Burgess Baptist Church in Crow Agency.  His other recording locations include camp meetings, private homes,  prayer services for the Crow Tribe, home prayer meetings,  and other religious gatherings on the reservation from 1985 to 1990s. The recordings also include copies of recordings given to Graber by Crow singers.
fields.provenance:
Robert Lowie recorded audio on wax cyclinders with Crow people on the reservation in the 1900s.  One of those recordings included a Crow hymn song by Max Big Man, a copy of which is part of the Graber recordings in this CIVAM collection. According to Peggy Well-Known Buffalo, Max and Gretchen Big Man and their children Annie, Carol Bull in Sight are well-known for singing these hymns. Lowie's original recordings are held at the Robert Lowie Museum of Anthropology at University of California, Berkeley.  
 
The Crow Bible Translation Committee in Pryor was formed in late 1960s and 1970s.  They recorded elders singing of Crow hymns. A Crow linguist began recording on cassette tapes in early 1970s.


1997 went from reel to reel to mini-disks.

In 1985, a committee of Crow people concerned about preserving the tradition sponsored the recording sessions and the Crow Hymns Project was organized.  They included David Graber, Georgine Falls Down, Sampson Bird in Ground,  Debbie Yarlott, Larry and Gwen Plain Bull, Joseph and Gloria Medicine Crow, David Turns Plenty, Mabel...

A Montana Humanities grant was awarded with the support of Dr. Janine Pease, then founder and president of Little Big Horn College, in 1989.
fields.citation: Crow Hymns collection, 1900-2018. Crow Indian Virtual Archive and Museum.
fields.historical_note:
Crow hymns are indigenous songs meant to connect Crow singing of Christia To paraphrase Joe Medicine Crow, Crow people heard the good news of Christianity at the turn of the century. They continued to seek the creator's wisdom in prayer and fasting at locations in the mountians identified with family fasting and praying locations.  Where a person would go to fast and pray without food or water for days at a time or until they received a vision, usually with a song.  WIth the coming of Christianity, this tradition became the source of many Crow hymns.  So the tune and the words expressed all were deeply embedded in Absalooke language, ways of thinking, and music.

The women allowed to be religious leaders in 19203-1930s.

Dave Graber knows when one song ends and another one begins, so he is able to splice the reel-to-reel into individual songs.
fields.location_of_originals: 24 reel to reel recordings are stored at the Little Big Horn College Archives.  Graber also has digital copies of those recordings in his private collection

fields.name: Black Lodge Farm Chapter, 1937
fields.description: Top photograph: "The Blacklodge Farm Chapter at play.  These recreation meetings occur frequently in the summer time. The top photograph depicts a feed (outdoor picnic or feast in local parlay). The bottom photograph depicts residents of the Black Lodge District of the Crow Reservation in 1937. Many of the men wear reservation hats, which were modified cowboy hats popular among Plains Indian men in the early to mid-20th century.  Regular cowboy hats and newsboy beanies are also on display. Along with those in modern outfits, many women are dressed in cotton print dresses, head scarves, and leather belts, which was typical fashion for Crow women at the time.
fields.other_forms: Originals: b&w glossy photograph, measuring, ca. 2 x 4.
fields.physical_details: Two black and white glossy photographs placed in paper brackets, attached to a page in a report.

fields.provenance: The photographs in this collection were published in the annual reports of the extension agent for the U.S. Department of Interior, Bureau of Indian Affairs, Division of Extension and Industry at the Crow Reservation. (The text of the reports has not yet been added to the CIVAM collection.) The report photographs were copied by Cindy Ott at the National Archives and Records Administration in Washington, D.C. in March 2015. Cindy Ott organized three exhibitions of a dozen of the photographs at senior centers in the towns of Crow Agency, Lodge Grass, and Pryor on the Crow reservation in summer 2017. (Catalog records of individual photographs document which ones were exhibited.)
fields.citation: Clarence S. Runyan, Agriculture Extension Agent, "Annual Report of Division of Extension and Industry, Crow Reservation, To Director of Extension and Industry, From January 31, 1937 to December 31, 1937.” United States Department of Interior, Office of Indian Affairs. National Archives and Records Administration, Washington, DC. Record Group 79: Bureau of Indian Affairs, Central Classified Files, 1907-1939, Crow 938-1937-031 to 54140-1938-031 Box 3 (PI- 163 E-121 HM 2001) Folder 330-1938 Crow 031 [2 of 2 folders]. CIVAM-NARA #9302.
fields.historical_note: The Crow reservation was divided into five agricultural districts, including Big Horn, Black Lodge, Lodge Grass, Pryor, and Reno  in 1891 and a sixth, Wyola, was added in 1894.

fields.description: Buffalo hide shield and cover. The green border on the left side of the shield represents the summer season, the crooked lines ending in knobs represent bullets glancing off the shield. The owl feathers represent the vision of a bird at night, and the eagle feathers the same for the day. The buffalo represents the carcass of that animal where the owner had his vision. Formerly owned by Hump (Apsáalooke). Video of Crow elder Tilton Old Bull and Peggy White Wellknown Buffalo describing the shield in Crow and English languages,  NMAI, 2005.

fields.name: Buffalo Shield and Cover with Bullet Hole Binnaaché
fields.description: Buffalo hide shield and cover. In the top is a bullet hole, and the last owner of the shield carried to the day of his death the bullet that penetrated the shield and imbedded itself above his right temple. The black perpendicular stripes represent clouds, the zig-zag lines lighting, the lower perpendicular lines rain, and the present represents the moon. The hawk attached to the middle is the war medicine of the original owner. The bundles of hawk feathers represent the hawk who gave the vision to the maker of the shield. Formerly owned by Sits In The Middle (Apsáalooke). Video of Crow elder Tilton Old Bull and Peggy White Wellknown Buffalo describing the shield in Crow and English languages,  NMAI, 2005.

fields.name: Mrs. L Walks Over Ice, Making Straight Rows, 1935
fields.description: "Mrs L Walks Over Ice, Makes Straight Rows." Mrs. L Walks Over Ice uses a tall tree branch to create holes in the ground to plant seeds.  A string is used to create straight rows. Walks Over Ice is dressed in the cotton print dress, head scarf, and leather belt popular in her day.  A young girl is in the field with her.

fields.name: Tommy Yellowtail Always has a Good Garden,1935
fields.description: "Tommy Yellowtail Always has a Good Garden"": Tommy Yellowtail, brother of Robert Yellowtail, was well-known for his gardening skills. The photograph focuses on rows that have been tilled and seeded and are  sprouting young plants. A house sits on the edge of the garden in the background. The garden is in the Lodge Grass District.

fields.private_notes:
Samantha Side emailed back and forth with Bill on May 7th this is what Bill said about the photo, 
"The red rimrocks surrounding Upper Lodge Grass Valley are most dramatic just at sunrise and sunset. These young Yellowtail cowhands are poised for a ride in the cool of the evening when cattle are most willing to move about. Brenda, Jim and Carson are Bill's younger siblings. The photo is from c. 1961."

fields.name: Kim and Cats
fields.description: Kimberly Dawn Yellowtail, daughter of Jeanne Eder and William Yellowtail, was born in Hanover, New Hampshire on May 9, 1970. Kim grew up on the Yellowtail family ranch. As seen in this photograph, she has always had a love for animals. Even before her teenage years, she became an accomplished cowhand and horsewoman, making her an indispensable part of the ranch's operation.

fields.private_notes:
This is a photograph of Bill's daughter, Kim. It was taken on the Yellowtail family ranch. I could not pinpoint the exact year that this photograph was taken, but because Kim was born in 1970 I can safely assume that this photo is from the 1970s.

I communicated with Bill via email on May 4, 2021 regarding this photograph. He wrote a description for me to use and edit as I saw fit: "Kimberly Dawn Yellowtail was born on May 9, 1970 in Hanover NH. Her mother is Jeanne Eder. Kim grew up on the Yellowtail family ranch, loving animals from cats to cowdogs, horses and cattle. As this photo attests, her interest came early. She became an accomplished cowhand and horsewoman even before her teenage years, and was an indispensable part of the ranch operation."
fields.citation: Kim and Cats, Yellowtail family ranch, Crow Reservation, MT, ca. 1970s. (Yellowtail, #28) Bill Yellowtail photographs, 1960s-2000s. Crow Indian Virtual Archive and Museum.

fields.description: "Effie Plenty Hawk of Pryor Another Good 4H Garden." Effie Plenty Hawk of Pryor stands in between the rows of crops in her garden on the reservation.  She holds a gardening tool and is dressed in a white dress, white stockings and a sweater.  Her entire suggests that she is dressed for visitors, not for actually working in the garden.  Her garden was probably a stop on a garden tour.

fields.name: Soap Creek 4-H Club, 1935
fields.description:
Top Photograph: "The members of the 4-H club at Soap Creek," 1935. This group of Indian and white girls learned gardening and home economics in the 4-H Club. All of the girls in the photograph have short bob haircuts, which became popular in the 1920s. 

Bottom Photograph: "John Buffalo, a member of the Soap Creek Club in his garden," 1935. John Buffalo, seen with braids, meets with an agricultural agent in his garden. A young Crow Indian boys also stands in the garden. The garden includes corn, among other crops.

fields.name: Crow Agency 4-H Garden Tour & Pious Real Bird, 4-H Member Showing His Garden, 1935
fields.description:
Top Photograph: "4-H Garden Tour, Crow Agency, July 1935"; Nicely dressed young men, women and children gather around a garden. The extension agent (fourth from left, with his back facing the camera), inspects the garden. 

Bottom Photograph: "Pious Real Bird, 4-H Member Showing His Garden"; Pious Real Bird is shown in blue jeans, reservation hat, and braids, walking in his garden with his back to the camera. A group of men, including extension agents, stand near a row of vegetables of some sort, while women and children are gathered around another part of the garden.

fields.name: "Lets Eat, "1935
fields.description:
Two Crow women  and two Crow men, surrounded by young children and other community members, pose during a "feed"- an outdoor picnic- in Big Horn County, Montana. Two tipis and several 1910s- or 1920s-era automobiles are in the background.

The women in the foreground, and those in the background, are pictured with scarves and printed dresses, which was popular attire for this period. Most of the women pictured have their heads covered, but the two women who are posed in front do not. All of the men pictured wear white shirts and hats. Most of the hats are reservation hats, a type of elongated cowboy hat, which was popular among Plains Indians around this time.

The tipis from this era had canvas covers, instead of buffalo hide. Traditionally, Crow families used the four-pole foundation. Poles could be twenty-feet in length.

fields.historical_note: Crow Fair has been an annual event on the Crow reservation since 1904. The Fair originated as an agricultural fair by the superintendent of the reservation Samuel Reynolds, but soon after Crows added events, including horse races, dances, and parades.

fields.name: Farm Chapter Meeting At Lodge Grass, 1935
fields.description: "Farm Chapter Meeting At Lodge Grass": This photograph depicts members of the Lodge Grass Farm District eating a meal outside, presumably before or after their chapter meeting.  Some of the participants sit on the ground and others at tables. Large gatherings where food is served are known as a "feed," on the reservation. Some of the men wear reservation hats. Due to the lack of leaves on the trees, it looks to be either late fall or early spring. Meetings such as this one were organized on a regular basis by the U.S. Department of Interior Extension Service to provide instruction about farm and garden practices to Indians and non-Indians on the reservation.

fields.description: Robin Iron Finding His 150 Head of Hereford Catlte, 1935:  View of Hereford cattle grazing in Robin Iron's pasture next his house by foothills.  Two men with a horse-drawn wagon piled with hay drop hay in a circle for the cattle. Two other outbuildings are visible.  Snow is on the distant mountain and no leaves are on the trees, marking the season as probably early spring.

fields.name: Black Hair Brothers Branding Their Spring Calf Crop, 1935
fields.description: "Black Hair Brothers Branding Their Spring Calf Crop": Two Black Hair Brothers, one a teenager, hold down a calf while another man (presumably another family member) brands the calf while the man who lassoed the calf watches from atop his horse. Other calves and their mothers wait in the corral for their turn.

fields.description: "Ellsworth Little Light Cutting Alfalfa with his New Mower":  Ellsworth Little Light sits on the back of his new horse-drawn mower to cut down his alfalfa field. fields.description: "Mrs. William Big Day of Pryor, Planting Potatoe by Hand": Mrs. William leans over the tilled soil in a cotton print dress to place potatoes in the ground for future harvest. Another farmer is seen in the distance with two horses, which gives a sense of the soil in which Mrs. William has left to plant.

fields.name: James Carpenter Digging His Crop of Potatoes Jim Sold $250 Worth of Early Potatoes
fields.description: "James Carpenter Digging His Crop of Potatoes Jim Sold $250 Worth of Early Potatoes": Jim and another man exchange $250 for a supply of potatoes, as four men stand beside them in a vast potato field. Also standing in the field are two horses, one of which is attached to a plow. The other horse is held in place as one man holds onto its reigns. To the right of the group is a dog as well, likely a Border Collie.

fields.description: "Mrs. Rob't Yellowtail and Anita Showing Their Excellent Garden": Mrs. Robert Yellowtail, also known as Margaret Yellowtail, and her daughter, Anita, stand within their home garden. fields.description: "Mrs. Eli Black Hawk Near Wyola Has a Well Balanced Garden": Mrs. Eli Black Hawk poses in her garden that has a variety of plants for future harvest. Mrs. Black Hawk wears a cotton printed dress, cinched at the waist with a belt, that opens in the front to show her pants and boots underneath. There are two houses that can be seen in the background, one closer than the other that may be the Black Hawk residence.

fields.name: Two of The Registered Stallions to Breed Saddle Mares, 1936
fields.description: "Two of The Registered Stallions That The Stockmen May Use Free to Breed Their Saddle Mares": Two Crow stockmen stand in front of a fence, each holding the reins of registered stallions- one saddled- that will be used for breeding free of charge. Both of the stockmen are dressed in cotton shirts and pants- one wears a cowboy hat, while the other only shows an arm and a leg. A house-like building is also shown behind the unsaddled stallion.

fields.description: "Two Delegates Were Sent by the Indian Clubs to Annual 4-H Club Conference at Bozeman": Two Crow boys stand side-by-side, with their arms straight at their side. They wear long white slacks, a black leather belt, a long sleeve dress shirt, a straight black tie with a tie clasp, and a garrison hat that leans to the side. The landscape is groomed. Two bushes and a line of trees create a dark shadow behind the two boys. A house slightly peaks between the breaks in the tree line.

fields.description: "The Crow Indian Reservation was represented at Midland Empire Fair": The Crow Reservation was able to represent themselves at the 1936 Midland Empire Fair. The Crow Reservation booth is covered in beautiful artwork and greenery and was a big attraction at the Fair. The Midland Empire Fair was started in 1916 and was a predominantly agricultural, livestock, and industrial fair held in Billings, Montana.

fields.name: The Present Home of Herbert Old Bear after the Rehabilitation Fund, 1936
fields.description: "The Present Home of Herbert Old Bear after the Rehabilitation Fund": This is the present home of Herbert Old Bear and his family. The Old Bear family, full of smiles, poses in front of their new home. The rehabilitation fund covered $350, leaving Old Bear only to pay $50 to purchase the new house. In today's money, $400, when accounting for inflation, equates to $7,746.62. To see where Herbert Old Bear and his family were living before visit "The home of Herbert Old Bear before the Rehabilitation Fund, 1936."

fields.name: The Home of Harry Don't Mix after the Repairs on his House, 1936
fields.description: "The Home of Harry Don't Mix after the Repairs on his House": After the rehabilitation loan, Harry Don't Mix was able to fix up his home, which included shingles, a new door, new windows, and a freshly drilled well. The well was particularly important to the family as it allowed them to have fresh drinking water without going to the irrigation ditch by the river.

fields.name: The Fourteen Head of Hereford Heifers Purchased by Arlis Whiteman with the Use of Rehabilitation Funds
fields.description: "The Fourteen Head of Hereford Heifers Purchased by Arlis Whiteman with the Use of Rehabilitation Funds": A dozen Hereford cows stand at the top of a grassy hill. In the distance are the Bighorn Mountains. To the right, at the bottom of the hill is a small house, which was likely owned by Arlis Whiteman.

fields.name: Wray Falls Down and Family Preparing and Planting Their Garden, 1936
fields.description: "Wray Falls Down and Family Preparing and Planting Their Garden": Wray Falls Down poses with his family as they prepare to plant their crops in their now barren garden. Wray stands in the foreground with a woman and two children- possibly preparing the untitled soil by hand- but a woman and another child are seen in the background as the child sets something in the soil, giving a sense of the garden's size. The women are wearing cotton dresses, while Wray and the boy are wearing cotton shirts and pants- Wray is also wearing a reservation hat.

fields.name: [Whenever Possible Crows Take Advantage of Power], 1936
fields.description: "Whenever it is Economically Possible the Crows Take Advantage of Power and Other Modern Machinery": Three Crow farmers configure a tractor-pulled plow to continue through the rough, unfenced terrain in the foreground. All three men are wearing cotton shirts and pants with cowboy hats.
fields.physical_details: One of two black and white glossy photographs placed in brackets, attached to a page in report.
fields.access_notes_or_rights_and_reproduction: All of these photographs are in the public domain and are, therefore, unrestricted in terms of access, use, and reproduction. However, we kindly ask those interested in using any image to contact relatives of the individuals depicted in the images for permission to use the images in any way. Please contact CIVAM at civam.mt@gmail for assistance.
fields.provenance: The photographs in this collection were published in the annual reports of the extension agent for the U.S. Department of Interior, Bureau of Indian Affairs, Division of Extension and Industry at the Crow Reservation. (The text of the reports has not yet been added to the CIVAM collection.) The report photographs were copied by Cindy Ott at the National Archives and Records Administration in Washington, D.C. in March 2015. Cindy Ott organized three exhibitions of a dozen of the photographs at senior centers in the towns of Crow Agency, Lodge Grass, and Pryor on the Crow reservation in summer 2017. (Catalog records of individual photographs document which ones were exhibited.)
fields.private_notes: The original report page only had a caption for 9015.1; however, the content of 9015.2 seemed to match the caption as well so I used the same caption for now in brackets to annotate the difference.
fields.citation: Charles S. Runyan, Agricultural Agent, U.S. Dept of Interior, Office of Indian Affairs, Field Service, “Annual Report of Division of Extension and Industry: Crow Reservation; To Director of Extension and Industry; From January 1, 1936 to December 31, 1936.” Records of Bureau of Indian Affairs (RG 75), Central Classified Files, 1907-39; Crow; 40761-1912-.023.1 To 130-1936-031; Box 2: PI-163 E-121 HM 2001. National Archives and Records Administration, Washington, D.C. CIVAM-NARA #9015.2
fields.location_of_originals: National Archives and Records Administration, Washington, D.C.

fields.name: Registered Belgian Stallion Purchased With Reimbursable Funds for Indian Draft Mares, 1936
fields.description: "Registered Belgian Stallion Recently Purchased With The Use of Reimbursablle Funds for The Use on The Indian Draft Mares": An unsaddled Belgian stallion stands in front of a grove of trees as the shadow of a person is cast next to it. This stallion was purchased with reimbursable funds so that it may be used to breed with Indian draft mares and has yet to be tacked up.

fields.name: Hide Shirt with Beadwork NMAI #102990.000] Baleiíttaashtee
fields.description: Hide shirt with fringe and beadwork on shoulders and chest.  The red, white and blue beadwork ornamentation on the chest includes strains of hair. Shoulder ornamentation uses yellow, red, dark blue, and light blue beads. Blue and red paint decorations overall. Long white ermine fur fringe with red elements attached.  Peggy Wellknown Buffalo is heard speaking in the Crow language in the video.
fields.physical_details: Hide, glass bead/beads, paint, hair, fur, wool cloth

fields.description: "WM. Lodgepole And A Crew of His Indian Neighbors Threashing William's Grain": William Lodge Pole has gathered some of his neighbors to thresh his grain via a threshing machine that can be seen near their closest pile of grain. There is a total of four men- all wearing cotton shirts and pants with reservation hats- two are examining the threshing machine, while the others are moving the grain.

fields.name: Bik baa ewahcheleetkaatak/ I don't know anything by myself, early 1900s
fields.description: Sheet music and QR code to play audio of the song Bik baa ewahcheleetkaatak/ I don't know anything by myself, early 1900s, recording in 1970s. The song is known as Maggie Brass' personal song. Larry Plain Bull, Pyror, Montana, sings the song along with his group, including his wife Gwen Plain Bull, and three other people  It is recorded by David Graber in Crow Agency in 1985. Most songs cannot be performed appropriately on a musical instrument because Native American scales vary widely.
fields.other_forms: Reel-to reel tape of an original recording are at Little Big Horn College Archives.  The reel-to-reel recording has not been divided into separate songs.
fields.physical_details: sheet music; QR code
fields.access_notes_or_rights_and_reproduction: The Crow hymns have been released by the consensus of the Crow Tribal Council and Crow Hymn Project for purposes of preservation, education and promotion in the Crow Nation, and beyond.  Crow Tribal Council Resolution #
fields.provenance: Reel-to reel tape of an original recording are at Little Big Horn College Archives and Dave Graber personal collection, Hardin, MT.
fields.private_notes: fix cover image
fields.citation: Maggie Brass, Bik baa ewahcheleetkaatak/ I don't know anything by myself, early 1900s. Hymn 1, Crow Hymn collection, Crow Indian Virtual Archive and Museum
fields.historical_note: It is more important to know who owned the song and had the rights to gift to human kind than it is to know who first created or received the song from the creator. The act of receiving a song was spiritual. They were often received during a vision quest.
fields.location_of_originals: The original recording is at the Little Big Horn College Archives.

The terrain is dry with small weeds peeking out of the soil. A tall wooden fence blocks the cattle from the surrounding hilly landscape. Behind the fence is a telephone poll and a building. A tree, which stands to the right, slightly obstructs the view of another structure.

fields.name: The Agency Calf Club
fields.description: "The Agency Calf Club": Sixteen young Crow boys are gathered in a group, with the first row of boys sitting on the ground, the second row kneeling, and the third row standing. One boy (to the top left) is wearing a reservation hat, while the boy kneeling in front of him is wearing a fedora. Some of the boys are holding up a paper sign, though the writing is not visible. To the left of the group is a dirt road and a line of trees. A wooden building stands on the other side of the dirt road. In the distance, behind the line of trees, is a house.

fields.content: The crew consists of every family member, a neighbor, and a couple of young men cousins. The boss, handling the hot branding iron, is Bill Yellowtail Sr. while Jane Yellowtail applies vaccinations. Curtis Hammond (brown hat) was a good neighbor and always traded help. Carson Yellowtail (bareheaded) and Arlen Whiteman “rassel” a calf while Bruce Yellowtail awaits his turn. Young Jim and Brenda Yellowtail handle their share, and Bill Yellowtail ropes calves on his white horse. “A Branding” is a serious and necessary task on the ranch, and custom calls for collaboration among neighbors and relatives. This is a diverse crew involving workers of all sizes, genders and ethnicities, the only qualification being skill and willingness to work hard. The owner of the cattle puts out the call for recruitment, and payment is a hearty meal or two.
fields.author: Bill Yellowtail

fields.content: Beaver dams create verdant habitats for all manner of wildlife, including adventuring kids. My brother and I enjoyed many whole days fishing, swimming and imagining there, returning home only in time for supper.
fields.author: Bill Yellowtail

fields.content:
This cow camp high in the Bighorn Mountains served as headquarters for a summer grazing permit. The sheep wagon was occupied by the boss, while the other cowhands slept in ‘range teepees' pitched nearby. After the crew experienced a screaming apparition, Cousin Larry pulled out and never returned.

Larry Dean Yellowtail, a first cousin, was regarded like a brother in the Crow kinship tradition. We grew up and cowboyed together on the cattle ranges of the Crow Reservation. Here, Larry prepares to ride out of the cow camp to monitor the family’s cattle on a grazing permit leased from the Tribe. Care for the cattle involves rides in the cool ends of the day -- dawn and twilight. The expression, “it don’t take long to stay all night on this outfit” reflects that schedule, but midday does afford time for a nap in the shade. Cowboys in camp play cards for chores, such as cooking, washing dishes, hauling wood and water, wrangling horses, and so on.
fields.author: Bill Yellowtail

fields.content: Neighbors convene to help each other with branding chores.
fields.author: Bill Yellowtail

fields.content: When an animal falls sick on the range, ranchers and cowboys must diagnose and treat. First, of course, the animal must be captured by a horseman wielding a lariat rope, immobilized and then medicated. Carson Yellowtail is an expert cattleman, horseman and roper on the open range, and here he and Larry Yellowtail have captured a sick calf. Usually a dose of antibiotic is a life-saver. Attending is Gary Spooner, a college friend of Bill’s from Vermont who spent two summers on the ranch. In this photo Gary has not yet acquired cowboy blue jeans but is beginning his steep learning curve to becoming a capable horseman and cowhand.
fields.author: Bill Yellowtail

fields.content: Ranchers customarily herd their livestock across each other's pastures. Here, a white rancher/neighbor and his cowhands trail beef steers through a Yellowtail pasture en route to the railroad for transport to market.
fields.author: Bill Yellowtail

fields.content: Elk, Iichiílikaashe, are plentiful in the Big Horn Mountains of the Crow Reservation with a population re-established by the Crow Tribe in the 1950s. Here, when I was a teenager, I gathered meat from a new kill. Hunting for food sustenance has long been an annual task and remains so today. Sport hunters usually regard the antlers of an elk as a trophy, but traditional Crows are disdainful of the practice. Accordingly, the antlers in this photograph were left in the field, while every bit of usable meat was collected.  (July 16, 2020)
fields.author: Bill Yellowtail

fields.content:
The cow camp is semi-permanent during the summer season on the family’s cattle grazing permit on the Bighorn Mountain section of the Crow Reservation. This campsite in the Bighorn Mountains has been in use for more than a century by stockmen tending cattle on the associated Crow Tribal grazing permit. Being adjacent to their private grazing allotments, the permit has been held by Yellowtails for almost all of that time. One or more cowboys occupy the camp and look after the cattle. I spent every summer of my youth living in that camp. Note that the tent is tattered by a marauding black bear. 

My parents Jane Powers and Bill Yellowtail met as young cowhands and eloped to marry in 1943 because her family objected to the relationship between a white woman and a Crow man. Ironically, marriages between white men and Indian women had been commonplace for more than a century.
fields.author: Bill Yellowtail

fields.content: Who needs a sled? A flattened cardboard box is a superior (and economical) vehicle for snow fun. Foothill slopes provide endless venues with degrees of steepness for every appetite for thrills. The only caveat with the cardboard conveyance is that one must choose a route reasonably free of large rocks. (July 16, 2020)
fields.author: Bill Yellowtail

fields.content: Drifted snow afforded vacation days from school for the Yellowtail kids. It was six miles across the foothills to the school bus stop, and Dad drove us there and back every school day, rain, snow or shine. The tribal road department seldom maintained the route. Dad would make a valiant effort to bust the road open with his ranch tractor, but sometimes the snowbanks won.
fields.author: Bill Yellowtail

fields.content: Storytelling is common ground for cowboys and Indians and Indian-cowboys. Bill Yellowtail Sr. and Dale Gibson were life-long neighbors on their adjoining ranches on the Crow Reservation. They enjoyed nothing more than telling and retelling stories by a campfire with a boiled pot of stout coffee. They shared the same landscape and sense of heritage – one the Crow and the other the white guy -- with no distance between them. The conversations extended from events of the day, to well-known tales of characters on the landscape, to recitations of traditional Crow or Irish legends. Dale could speak a little Crow language. With skills honed over lifetimes of these sessions, both cowboys and Indians treasure a singular ability to transform a mundane event into a hilarious story. Teasing is a high art. The smart young person will practice good listening and respectful quietude. Just keep the coffee cups full.
fields.author: Bill Yellowtail

fields.content: Robin Iron was a good roper. He was known for his roping and as a cattleman. He worked for P.R. Krone.  Krone leased on the reservation around Fort Smith, at the bottom of the mountain. Krone's brand was T down, T up.  His ranch was near Fort Smith. Nothing but cattle on the land there when I was a boy.  He leased all that land.  He leased land from my grandma Mary Old Rabbit, my dad's mother. Mary Old Rabbit was Old Lady Cashen's sister. Their ranch was right in St. X. It was a two story house. All of them were pretty well off. They had nothing to worry about. (June 6, 2021)
fields.author: Tronson Big Hair

fields.content: The red rimrocks surrounding Upper Lodge Grass Valley are most dramatic just at sunrise and sunset. These young Yellowtail cowhands are poised for a ride in the cool of the evening when cattle are most willing to move about. Brenda, Jim, and Carson are Bill's younger siblings. The photo is from c. 1961.
fields.author: Bill Yellowtail

fields.content: Percy Stops Indian name Goes to See the Tobacco - [oh-be-dal-ish]. His wife's name was Good River [Ah-be-tish] (June 6, 2021) He lived on the west side of the railroad tracks in Garryowen.  They were farmers.  They had horses, stacked their own hay.
fields.author: Tronson Big Hair

fields.content: At the early reservation time, women in the tribe had no authority to speak in public. Maggie Brass had a gift for ministering to people in public gatherings, and she was using her gift to speak and minister publicly.  She was criticized for this because she was a woman.  In her discouragement, she prayed for guidance, and was given this song. It is one of many attributed to her. -Statement by Angela Russell, descendant of Maggie Brass
fields.author: Angela Russell

fields.content: Maggie Brass wanted the song to last beyond her life, so she shared it.  She said keep sharing this song because it was a blessing to her ministry.
fields.author: Dave Graber

fields.history: The Field Museum in Chicago, Illinois hosted the exhibit "Apsáalooke Women and Warriors" from March 13 to July 18, 2021. The exhibit featured the work of 20 Crow artists ranging from fashion, to paint, sculpture, beadwork, film, music, and photography. The exhibit was curated by Apsáalooke scholar, Nina Sanders, with support from the Apsáalooke Nation and other Native artists and scholars. The exhibition was organized by the Field Museum in collaboration with the Neubauer Collegium for Culture and Society at the University of Chicago.
fields.notes:
- 39 historic objects from the Field Museum's collection, including 7 war shields, were included in the Apsáalooke Women and Warriors exhibit
- 22 works by contemporary Apsáalooke artists, including Elias Not Afraid, Ben Pease, Birdie Red Bird, Kevin Red Star, Adam Sings In The Timber, Bethany Yellowtail, and others are featured in the exhibit

fields.history: The Chadron State College under the direction of Alex Coon held an exhibition show Crow History, language, and culture to students of the college and to residents of the town of Chadron, Nebraska. In photos in appears that they had Crow artifacts on display.
fields.notes:
Alex Coon in 2015, set up the exhibit as a way of show Crow history and language with educational kiosks to help students learn. 
Number for contact of the center:  308-432-6401
The contact email:  spolak@csc.edu
Unsure if they have a permanent collection, it is clear that in 2015 they had an exhibit with crow artifacts.

fields.name: Museum of the Plains Indian
fields.history: The Museum of the Plains Indian was founded in 1941 and displays richly varied arts of Northern Plains Tribal peoples including the Blackfeet, Crow, Northern Cheyenne, Sioux, Assiniboine, Arapaho, Shoshone, Nez Perce, Flathead, Chippewa, and Cree. Their historic clothing, horse gear, weapons, household implements, baby carriers, and toys highlight the exhibits.
fields.notes:
The Museum of the Plains Indian is managed by the U.S. Department of the Interior, Indian Arts and Crafts Board.

fields.name: The University of Pennsylvania Museum of Archaeology and Anthropology
fields.history:
The University of Pennsylvania Museum of Archaeology and Anthropology, commonly called the Penn Museum, has hundreds of Crow Indian objects in their possession. 

In a 1926 journal article from The Museum Journal, author Alden J. Mason writes about the museum's Crow Indian collection. The article can be found here: https://www.penn.museum/sites/journal/1432/
fields.notes: The Crow Indian Collection was secured by the Museum from Mr. Ernest E. Murray of Billings, Montana.

fields.name: The National Museum of the American Indian
fields.history: The National Museum of the American Indian (NMAI) cares for one of the world's most expansive collections of Native artifacts, including objects, photographs, archives, and media covering the entire Western Hemisphere, from the Arctic Circle to Tierra del Fuego.
fields.notes: The NMAI has over 1,000 Crow Indian objects in its collection.

fields.name: The Baltimore Museum of Art
fields.notes:
The Baltimore Museum of Art has various Crow objects in their possession. Their virtual collection can be found on their website. 

The museum is also home to artwork created by Wendy Red Star, Apsáalooke (Crow). Raised on the Apsáalooke (Crow) reservation in Montana, Wendy Red Star is a visual artist who engages in various creative expressions including photography, sculpture, video, fiber arts, and performance.

fields.name: Natural History Museum of Utah
fields.history: Leggings, belt buckles, jewelry, moccasins, along with other clothing items and tools are held within the museum's Archeological Collection. According to the Natural History Museum of Utah, the majority of these items were donated in 1998 by Anthony H. Taylor, a Utah-based artist and teacher. Taylor donated 750 American Indian artifacts, which he collected over 50 years.

fields.content: The Crow Indian Virtual Archive & Museum (CIVAM) is a virtual repository of Crow Indian cultural items and images housed in public and private collections around the world.

• To collect, curate, and interpret digital representations of Crow materials for Crow Indians and all others interested in Crow history and culture
  • To re-acquaint Crow Indians with materials removed from their reservation community so that these items and images can contribute to the on-going cultural life of Crow people
  • To provide Crow elders with access to these materials so that they can explain their meaning and significance, improve the items’ attributions, and educate younger generations about them
  • To maintain a digital storehouse of Crow family heirlooms currently held in private homes to document Crow culture all the way to the present.

Peggy White Wellknown Buffalo had a vision to help, as she said, “the generations in front us to have an understanding and knowledge of their roots.” She went to her clan father and brother Leroy White and to the Crow Nation Chairperson Clara Nomee. Both gave Wellknown Buffalo permission to fulfill her vision to re-acquaint the Crow Indian community with items that had long-ago been removed from the reservation. Chairman Nomee specifically gave Wellknown Buffalo written permission to access Crow Indian collections at the Smithsonian Institution’s National Museum of American Indian (NMAI) in 2001.

Susie Kelly helped Wellknown Buffalo recruit and arrange for Crow elders Tilton Tall Bull and Clayton Mountain Picket to visit the NMAI in Washington, DC. To paraphrase Wellknown Buffalo: The mission was for those people to come forward with knowledge about the cultural items. Our bundles are dying, because almost no one is left with knowledge about them.

Kelly and Wellknown Buffalo led seven trips to the NMAI between 2001 and 2008. Kelly and Wellknown Buffalo videotaped Old Bull and Mountain Picket as they examined and described the history and stories about the sacred and non-sacred items there. Wellknown said, “The bundles wanted to breathe. I prayed over each bundle and asked it permission to be opened.”

For ten years, the videotapes of the elders’ encounters with the items stored at the national museum sat at The Center Pole compound without seeing the light of day. Wellknown Buffalo and Kelly were concerned that Wellknown Buffalo’s vision would not come to fruition.

In the summer of 2018, University of Delaware Professor Cindy Ott visited her friends at The Center Pole and happened to ask Wellknown Buffalo and Kelly if there was a material culture project that Ott and her students could help them with. It was a fortuitous question that led to the creation of the Crow Indian Virtual Archive and Museum. Wellknown Buffalo gave Ott permission to create CIVAM because, she said, Ott is an educator. Wellknown Buffalo and Kelly were relieved that the items would no longer be in storage, but would be “used to educate others, to open up minds to what happened in our past. I would love to have my great-great-granddaughter learn about them in school. Lots of stories are now lost. This is for the future of our children. That is why this is important to me,” Wellknown Buffalo said.

The CIVAM is maintained by students, staff, and faculty at the University of Delaware Departments of History, Museum Studies, and Computer Science with support from the UNIDEL Foundation and in collaboration with The Center Pole on the Crow reservation in Montana. Please send queries to civam.mt@gmail.com.

"Ba La Se She Lesh" (She Who Wears the Money) grew up traditional Crow. Sent away to Indian boarding schools at a young age, she has nurtured more than two hundred children in her home as an adult. She practices the Crow sweat lodge and has sponsored numerous Native American Church prayer meetings. With Susie Kelly, she runs The Center Pole, a Native non-profit organization founded in 1999 on the Crow Indian Reservation in Montana and spearheads many community development projects, including the CIVAM.

"Dek Gash Bish" (Woman Eagle) helped Peggy create the Center Pole in 1999, bringing practical skills to blend with traditional ways. Originally a photo editor, researcher, writer and project manager in the publishing industry, she brought up multicultural children and worked providing promising youth with opportunities for many years. Her motto: Start where you are...Use what you have...Do what you can--Arthur Ashe.

Cindy is an Associate Professor of History and Material Culture Studies at the University of Delaware. She began her career at the Smithsonian Institution in the 1980s and she has continued to develop public humanities projects ever since. After serving as the history curator at the Museum of the Rockies in Bozeman, Montana from 2004 to 2006, she started spending summers on the Crow reservation in Montana. She has been working on a local ranch, helping out at The Center Pole, and conducting research for her book Biscuits and Buffalo: The Reinvention of American Indian Culture in the 20th and 21st Centuries.

A special thanks for their great efforts and dedication to the project goes to UD software engineering students:

Mark Wolgin, Nathan Joseph, Timothy Mazzarelli, Joshua Davis, Nicholas Fafel, Samuel Shultis, Johnny Pabst, Andrew Thompson, Brian Bugieda, Sam Zabaldo, Evan MacGregor, Emily Kresho, Jason Belak, Brianna Emrich, Sophia Freaney, Joy Kitson, Christopher Outhwaite, Trevor Seidel, James Skripchuk, and Karl Stomberg

And to humanities students:

Ellie Gorman, Adam Grimes, Danielle Haugk, Grace McKeon, Matthew Monk, Megan O’Donell, Fabian Martin Rempfer, Ryan Wood, and Sophie Zaidman who helped envision it.

• To find out more about CIVAM and to access collections, please contact civam.mt@gmail.com
  • The Center Pole
More Collections will be added soon!
Look at a map that will show you Crow items from around the world.
More collections will be added soon!

This map shows the location of Crow items in museums around the world.  Its purpose is to track and identify Crow items that have been distributed far and wide from the reservation in Montana.  Eventually, CIVAM will include the history of how the items got to their various locations and we hope to include images of the items in our collection.  Finally, we hope the Map inspires interesting discussions about the worldwide distribution of Crow items.  Do you think the distribution of Crow items a form of colonialism or cosmopolitanism?
